column1: When will Fitch, Moody's, or S&P next downgrade the United Kingdom's long-term local or foreign currency issuer ratings?
column5: ['Before 30 March 2019', 'Between 30 March 2019 and 31 July 2019, inclusive', 'Between 1 August 2019 and 31 December 2019, inclusive', 'Not before 1 January 2020']
column6: ['Economic Indicators', 'Non-US Politics']
column11: Revisions to the "outlook" will not suffice. S&P and Fitch last downgraded the United Kingdom after the 2016 Brexit vote, and Moody's did the same in September 2017 (The Associated Press, Reuters). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

column6: S&P and Fitch just signaled that the UK, for now, is stable. Everyone is watching to see what happens next. There is unlikely to be an rating changes.

Not before January but maybe at some point next year? Per the Economist: “Whoever wins the general election on December 12th will have reason to worry about the economy. Purchasing managers’ indices aim to take the pulse of business, and for now they point to an economy on the slide. Monday’s manufacturing data and Tuesday’s construction survey showed both those industries contracting. Today it was the turn of the all-important service sector, supposedly the economy’s great strength. It was equally gloomy; new orders fell at their fastest pace since mid 2016. PMIs in Britain tend to overshoot on both the downside and upside. In July 2016, immediately after the Brexit referendum, they pointed towards an imminent recession which never arrived. They are still worth watching though. And the picture they paint is consistent with other data sources and most forecasters. Brexit and wider political uncertainty are holding back investment, and growth looks likely to be under 1.5% next year. That will keep the public finances under pressure, leaving less room for the giveaways that all parties are pledging.”

Credit rating agencies tend to move cautiously on their ratings for the major sovereigns, including the UK. Prior to 2013, the UK ratings had been unchanged by any agency for decades [1]. Following the Brexit vote in 2016, all three rating agencies have already downgraded the UK : S&P and Fitch within days of the referendum vote, while Moody's didn't downgrade until over a year later (useful table and charts here [2]). Fitch indicated in February 2019 that they might make a change if a "hard Brexit" occurs [3].

I estimate possible outcomes on or before the 29th of March as hard Brexit (25%), Brexit with a last-minute deal (25%), Brexit being delayed (40%) or Brexit being aborted (10%). I think a downgrade is quite likely to occur soon after the 29th of March in the 'hard Brexit' case, but with a deal or delay there's a smaller chance of a downgrade and it could be sooner or later (or beyond in 2020). I think it's unlikely to occur before the 29th of March, because if they were going to make a move based on uncertainty they would have done so already.

Adjusting pre-March, 30th probability down, given comments from all 3 agencies on a wait-and-see approach. I can't find anything to suggest a shifting view.

In almost all cases ratingare not a leading indicator of a worse creditworthiness, but follow the market risk spreads. Actaally, risk spreads have widened significantly over 2018, but are sill low by historical standards. Thus, currently the market indicate no downgrade. However, it is of course totally possible that risk spreads will widen due to a chaos Brexit and in fact, I expect a no-deal Brexit and a recession in the UK, but I currently do not think that this will be enough to harm the UK and endanger government debt payments so much that a rating downgrade would be justified. A main difference between the UK and many other economis is, that the UK is indebted more or less only in its own currency, so that even a strong exchange rate fluctuation does not lead to a rise of real debt.
